# ðŸ“„ Create, View, and Edit Text Files in Linux  
Useful Linux commands to manage text files with simple explanations, real-world scenarios, and issue fixes.

---

## ðŸŸ¢ 1. Creating Files

### **1. touch**
Creates an empty file (or updates timestamp if file already exists).

```bash
touch file.txt

Use case:
Create multiple files for configuration/testing.

touch app.log error.log config.yaml

2. echo + redirect (>)

Creates a file with text inside.

echo "Hello World" > hello.txt


Use case:
Creating a quick configuration file.

echo "PORT=8080" > .env

3. cat (create file)
cat > notes.txt


(Type text, then press: CTRL + D to save)

Use case:
Writing a quick note or message in a text file.

ðŸ”µ 2. Viewing Files
1. cat

Displays entire file content.

cat file.txt

2. head

Shows the first 10 lines (default).

head file.txt

3. tail

Shows the last 10 lines.

tail file.txt


Real-time scenario:
View the latest logs updating on a server.

tail -f /var/log/messages

4. less

Scroll through the file (best for long files).

less /etc/passwd

ðŸŸ¡ 3. Editing Files
1. nano (Beginner-friendly)
nano file.txt


Keys:

CTRL + O â†’ save

CTRL + X â†’ exit

2. vi / vim (Advanced)
vi file.txt


Modes:

Press i â†’ Insert mode

Type text

Press Esc â†’ Command mode

Type :wq â†’ save and exit

ðŸŸ£ 4. Real-Time Scenarios
Scenario 1: Create a log file and view it
touch app.log
echo "Application started" >> app.log
tail -f app.log

Scenario 2: Update a configuration file
echo "DB_HOST=localhost" > config.ini
nano config.ini

Scenario 3: Read the last 50 lines of a log file
tail -n 50 /var/log/secure

Scenario 4: Merge multiple files
cat part1.txt part2.txt > final.txt

ðŸ”´ 5. Common Issues & Solutions
âŒ Issue: Permission denied while editing a system file
nano /etc/hosts


Solution: use sudo

sudo nano /etc/hosts

âŒ Issue: Overwriting file by mistake

You used > instead of >>

echo "new line" > data.txt   # overwrote file âŒ


Fix: Always use append >> when unsure

echo "new line" >> data.txt

âŒ Issue: File not found
cat myfile.txt


Solution: Check directory

ls -l
pwd

âŒ Issue: Cannot exit vi/vim

You are stuck in vim ðŸ˜…

Solution:

Press ESC
Type :q!   â†’ Quit without saving  
Type :wq   â†’ Save and quit

ðŸŸ¢ Summary Table
Task	Command	Description
Create empty file	touch f.txt	Creates new file
Create file with text	echo "text" > f.txt	Overwrites/creates
View file	cat f.txt	Show content
Paginated view	less f.txt	Scroll inside file
Edit file	nano f.txt	Beginner editor
Edit file	vi f.txt	Advanced editor
Follow logs	tail -f log.txt	Live logs
